    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer880303284" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7557743142075718760">Today marks the 50th anniversary of the Independence of Bangladesh. <br/><br/>It has been 50 years since Bangladeshis decided to rise up against tyranny and take back their identity (at the time they were called East Pakistan) and land from West Pakistan. As a person with Bangladeshi roots, this alone fills me with pride, that a tiny nation, without the matching military power to go up against its oppressors, still went to war and came out victorious after 9 gruelling months. But the reason this day is ev</span>
  <span id="freeText7557743142075718760" style="display:none">Today marks the 50th anniversary of the Independence of Bangladesh. <br /><br />It has been 50 years since Bangladeshis decided to rise up against tyranny and take back their identity (at the time they were called East Pakistan) and land from West Pakistan. As a person with Bangladeshi roots, this alone fills me with pride, that a tiny nation, without the matching military power to go up against its oppressors, still went to war and came out victorious after 9 gruelling months. But the reason this day is even more important for me, is because my dad, a 15 year old teen back in 1971, had sneaked out in the middle of the night and gone to join the ‘Mukti Bahini’ (guerrilla resistance) and become a rebel freedom fighter willing to lay down his life for love of country. He was one of the youngest soldiers registered and even the day before he passed away, he scribbled on to a pad, barely able to hold a pen, that he wanted freedom fighter to be engraved on his tomb marker.<br /><br />One of my biggest regrets in life is that I never asked, or even had the foresight while he was sick to ask, about his journey in 1971 - how he left home against his parents’ wishes, where he travelled to, how did he join, where was he stationed, what did he eat, where did he sleep, was he shot at, did he shoot anyone, did he lose a friend, what was the most horrifying thing he witnessed, what was his proudest moment then?? So many question but I was too young to know to ask them, to record this history. Breaks my heart and I’ll kick myself to my dying day for not having his whole story. I guess even my dad didn’t think to tell me about all the horrors of war and by the time he realized he was passing away, it was too late. Now I just have snippets and large blanks. Anyways, I can go on and on about my father and what a unique man he was, but back to the book. <br /><br />A Golden Age by Tahmima Anam is primarily a mother’s story, her struggles, emotions, choices, and experiences during the Bangladesh War of Independence. I had picked up this book long ago, to help fill some of those gaps, and although it didn’t give a sweeping history of the war and did take you through a wide scale of experiences, it was still enough. I would have rated it a 3.5 but Anam got 4 stars because the writing was very beautiful. Now I have a taste, and I want to devour all the books I can to continue filling those blanks in my dad’s story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7557743142075718760" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

