    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3747548023" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3747548023" />
    <a title="Laavanya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49271290-laavanya"><img alt="Laavanya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598230079p2/49271290.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3747548023?book_show_action=true">Jan 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laavanya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laavanya" href="/user/show/49271290-laavanya">Laavanya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Anyone who is interested in South Asia</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3747548023" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15749710946431357096">Over the years, I have read so many books from South Asian writers especially about immigration, bi-cultural identity, being torn between two cultures, and the country of your birth and the one you adopted. It was only recently over the course of 2020, I began to read more in depth about the Partition of India and the reasons behind it : the Pakistan movement, South Asian Muslim nationalism, and the two-nation theory that Hindus and Muslims were 2 separate nations. Many Partition books alluded t</span>
  <span id="freeText15749710946431357096" style="display:none">Over the years, I have read so many books from South Asian writers especially about immigration, bi-cultural identity, being torn between two cultures, and the country of your birth and the one you adopted. It was only recently over the course of 2020, I began to read more in depth about the Partition of India and the reasons behind it : the Pakistan movement, South Asian Muslim nationalism, and the two-nation theory that Hindus and Muslims were 2 separate nations. Many Partition books alluded to the the break up of East Pakistan from West Pakistan and that it became Bangladesh. Until I read this book, I had no idea the horrors of war and the mistreatment that the Bengali Muslims went through at the hands of the Pakistani government and army. <br /><br />In all the books on Partition I read, this is one of the ones that just tore my heart. How could I, an Indian American women, not ever have been told or read about the genocide committed against the Bengali Muslims and Hindus of East Pakistan by the Pakistani army? The author went detail into detail about the human rights violations that occurred during the 9 month Bangladeshi war of liberation. I ended the last page in tears. This was a work of fiction, the characters and the story line were strong and added to the poignant book. <br /><br />The fire of the Bengali spirit touched my heart many years ago, and I love the language, its culture and everything these people have stood for. I have never seen a people who are so proud of their language and culture, to love it so much that they were ready to die for their nation to come into existence. They were not willing to allow another language, culture and injustices done to them to take way their right to be Bengali. I salute all those lives that were lost to give birth to Bangladesh. Long live the spirit of Bengal! <br /><br />This book has forced me to think of some major things.<br /><br />The question I would ask the founders of Pakistan, Jinnah and the Muslim League is this : if the Muslims of South Asia were one ummah, how come the Pakistani government and army did what they did to their fellow Bengali Muslim brothers? Why does your government continue to deny the full extent of the genocide of the Bengali Muslims? The existence of Bangladesh shows me that the two nation theory is flawed and not completely valid. Otherwise we would not have Bangladesh today.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15749710946431357096" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

